Gary Danko, now whoever came up with that name is an absolute genius. I can honestly say that whenever i am taken or surprised to come here for dinner, i get chills coming down my spine, flushed and ooo so many things I care not to express.. Gary Danko is one of those place that you just have to appreciate their superb ambience, services and the food. Gary Danko is not just a high reputable and pricey restaurant but it is a dining experience. From the moment you enter into Gary Danko, it is a world that is far beyond your wildest imagination in regards to eating and dining. The ensemble casts of hosts and waiters make Gary Danko what it is today. They are so warm and friendly and their impeccable services are to be reckon. My bf took me for my surprised birthday celebration here. The best gift of all is no other than......Gary Danko. I decided as usual to go with the 3 course meals in anyway and form i like. I decided to go with the two appetizers which were the crab corn soup along with the crab salad. The crab corn soup is so heavenly and smooth with the right taste to perfection. The crab salad is my favorite here at Gary Danko and never cease to disappoint. And lastly my main entree is the Quailed stuff with foie gras and mushroom. It just melts in your mouth. It is oooo sooo good. And to pair it up with a German Reisling just complete this 5 stars meal. Not to mentioned, their cheese selections are highly recommended along with the raspberry souffle. It is just so good that you just feel like you died and gone to dessert Gary Danko heaven. I am always taken back how they make your evening and especially on a day like a birthday even more special, by just a small gesture of just appreciating that you came to dine with them. Lastly, they always give you a handful of differents small types of dessert nipplers to sample. They are always so small but yet so good. And as a small token of their appreciation before you leave, a small bake good wrapped neatly in a foil Gary Danko to take home. Now I say WoW! Gary Danko is not just a restaurant, it is a dining experience that I will forever appreciate and will continue to make it my favorite restaurant to go to in all occasions.

This restaurant hardly needs another great review, but I'm going to give it! My girlfriend and I had the most amazing meal I've ever had! Everything was wonderful!! The quail was definitely my favorite. We made reservations two months ahead of time when we decided to take a trip to San Fran. Before we ordered, the waiter brought out a soup that was to die for (lentil maybe?). Everything was just a blur of mouth watering goodness. And to top it all off, the chef made banana bread for us to take home for breakfast (the most amazing banana bread I've ever had, I called my mom and told her she needs to step her game up). Totally worth every penny!!

So I've always wanted to try Gary Danko at least once in my life just to see what all the hype is about and why you must make reservation months in advance. When you make reservation two months in advance it's easy to get dinner times around 5ish or 9ish at night. If you want a better time, maybe try calling in few months before hand? The restaurant looks pretty small so tables get booked fast. Apparently, Gary Danko has been rated #1 for the past 5 years in Zagat Survey. Now Kokkari bumps Gary Danko from #1 in 2015. I've only tried the salad at Kokkari, and food is most definitely less expensive, but not sure if I would purposely go there and try the other food. What I enjoy about fine dinning is the good service. Whatever you need, they will assist you with the best of their ability. Everyone was really polite. Water was always filled. Food came in a timely manner. They always came to see if everything was okay and if we had any questions. The ambience was great, not too noisy so you can chat with whomever you're dinning with. The only down side was tables were too close so it feels a tad cramp and not enough personal space; however, beautiful decors every where. We started off with a complimentary soup, root vegetable pureee? I actually do not remember the exact name, but it was very flavorful. I enjoyed it, but I would not want a small bowl of it since the taste was strong. A small amount was just perfect. We had the Seared Ahi Tuna with Avocado, Nori, Enoki Mushrooms and Lemon Soy Dressing as the appetizer. The color of the ahi tuna looked really good and fresh as for the taste, it was even better. The lemon soy dressing taste kind of vinaigrette-ish to me and it was great with the dish. I would've wanted to order two of this if I had known. The Seared sea scallops with sun choke puree, leek fondue and salsify was really juicy and soft. The sauce was very flavorful and great combo with the scallop. It only came with two big scallops so I would like second for this as well. The Coconut Thai Curry with shrimp, calamari, lobster, scallops, scallions and shiitake mushrooms was very creamy. I'm totally not a fan of coconut but this dish was not bad. Everything was a good blend, but not something I would want a whole lot of. It's most definitely worth giving it a try.The Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Celery root garlic puree, spinach and cardamom poached pears had a really nice presentation. The duck looked like it was going to be juicy but when I start to eat it, it was dry and took a while to chew. The celery root garlic puree was not fabulous since it didn't give the duck an extra kick to me. I just ate the duck alone and tried to add more salt and pepper on it since it seem like it lack flavor which did not help. The Roasted Pork Tenderloin with Pork belly, squash, brussels sprouts, apple and chestnuts also had a really good presentation as well, but it was only ok to me. Pork belly was really soft, too much fat to my liking, but my bf enjoyed it. To me the pork tenderloin was a tad better than the duck because it wasn't as dry feel, but still very chewy. Flavor was good though, especially the vegetables. I'm more likely to order the pork over the duck again. The Herb Crusted Loin of Lamb with Farrotto, Medjool Dates, Rainbow carrots and green chermoula did not taste gamy but it did not wow me. Again very chewy like the other meats. I could barely finish half. There was an extra patty in the dish, it taste weird, I did not enjoy it. Most definitely will not order this dish again.The Seared Filet of beef with swiss chard, potatoes, shallot marmalade and bordelaise butter looked great. The beef was cooked perfectly to medium rare and was really soft. The only down side was not enough flavoring. After adding more salt and pepper to the beef made it taste so much better. If I haven't tried so many other dishes before hand, I would've enjoy this dish a lot more. I would give this another try. Dessert was Strawberry Souffle with strawberry Sauce and strawberry sorbet, and Baked chocolate Souffle with two sauces. Souffles were the things I was looking forward to most. Never tried them before and always thought it would be amazing. Little did I expect to be disappointed. I did not enjoy any of the souffles. The chocolate was too chocolatey to me even though it's one of the popular ones there. The strawberry was better but still didn't enjoy it. They were very fluffy and light. I did not enjoy them, but i'm not indicating they are bad desserts though. Maybe they just weren't meant for me. My bf said the ones he made taste better. I have nothing to compare it to since it was my first time trying them. Overall, I will come again to try other dishes. Most definitely affordable dinner. Only down side, must reserve months in advance. =/

Twas a magical night on the 17th of January.... Gary Danko has now made it as my go to comparison for everything I'm willing to spend money on.... Should I buy new tires for my car? No, it could wait because for that price I can eat at Gary Danko 3 times... Everything we ate was orgasmic, but the two dishes that I would do some shady stuff for are the Glazed Oysters and the Louisiana Butter Cake. My dining companion is just as difficult to please as I am when it comes to fine dining. We have been to numerous of overrated restaurants where the food is not as great as what others hype it up to be and we are glad that Gary Danko is not one of them! We finally got the chance to try this place out after a 2 month reservation wait and I can say for those who haven't been here before, this place is exceptionally good and worth coming to. The flavors were unusual, in the most wonderful way. What's different about this place is that rather than paying for the price of each entree like most restaurants, you are to select either a 3, 4 or 5 course dinner which is priced at $73, $92 and $107 respectively. You then choose from their vast menu selection the meals you would like categorized under appetizer, fish and seafood, meat, cheeses & dessert. What's great about picking your entrees is that you're not limited to selecting only one meal per category. It's really an endless possibility; you can even have a 5 course dinner with all desserts if you like! The meals were all fantastic and amazing. My top 2 entrees I'd have to recommend to potential diners is their Lemon Pepper Duck and Roast Maine Lobster. Considering I'm not a big fan of duck meat, this place cooked it to perfection for me. It was very tender, juicy and will literally melt in your mouth at first bite. It's absolutely worth coming here to try; you'll taste the difference from every where else. The lobster entree came with a side of creamy potatoe puree and sauteed mushrooms. The lobster was delicious blasting with flavor in every bite. The potatoe puree was a first for me and I must say, I'd prefer this over mashed potatoes! The other dishes we enjoyed were all phernomenal and fulfilling as well. While our meals were fantastic and very satisfying, the detail and quality of ingredients used is really what gives this place the full 5 stars. The service here is fantastic - prompt, accomodating and professional. The operation here is well-executed and this place is definitely a legit option for dinner.

We had an great meal here as expected. The food itself was all very good, though in some ways it did not make as big an impression as other restaurants of this ilk that we've liked. We got dungeness crab salad, risotto, juniper bison, peanut butter bar for dessert, and other things I don't remember. The wine list is overwhelmingly long, but we ended up liking the french burgundy we got. The service was superb, we really liked our waiter. The little plate of tiny sweets served at the end and the two take-home mini-loafs and banana bread are nice touches.

I've celebrated my birthday here a few years ago and returned for my birthday again. Great meal and excellent service. They even gave me a birthday gift to go. Street parking isn't too bad either. We were within one block both times.

I think I can sit down and write a few pages on what I enjoyed here on a recent visit but to make things simple and to the point. I took a client here and they were very delighted with my choice. If you are thinking about trying Gary Danko and can budget it if that is a concern then go. The food is amazing and the portions were hearty. We did the five course dining option along with the wine pairing and we were very happy. Go make your reservation. =)

The Seared sea scallops with sun choke puree, leek fondue and salsify was really juicy and soft. The sauce was very flavorful and great combo with the scallop. It only came with two big scallops so I would like second for this as well. The Coconut Thai Curry with shrimp, calamari, lobster, scallops, scallions and shiitake mushrooms was very creamy. I'm totally not a fan of coconut but this dish was not bad. Everything was a good blend, but not something I would want a whole lot of. It's most definitely worth giving it a try.The Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Celery root garlic puree, spinach and cardamom poached pears had a really nice presentation. The duck looked like it was going to be juicy but when I start to eat it, it was dry and took a while to chew. The celery root garlic puree was not fabulous since it didn't give the duck an extra kick to me. I just ate the duck alone and tried to add more salt and pepper on it since it seem like it lack flavor which did not help. The Roasted Pork Tenderloin with Pork belly, squash, brussels sprouts, apple and chestnuts also had a really good presentation as well, but it was only ok to me. Pork belly was really soft, too much fat to my liking, but my bf enjoyed it. To me the pork tenderloin was a tad better than the duck because it wasn't as dry feel, but still very chewy. Flavor was good though, especially the vegetables. I'm more likely to order the pork over the duck again. The Herb Crusted Loin of Lamb with Farrotto, Medjool Dates, Rainbow carrots and green chermoula did not taste gamy but it did not wow me. Again very chewy like the other meats. I could barely finish half. There was an extra patty in the dish, it taste weird, I did not enjoy it. Most definitely will not order this dish again.The Seared Filet of beef with swiss chard, potatoes, shallot marmalade and bordelaise butter looked great. The beef was cooked perfectly to medium rare and was really soft. The only down side was not enough flavoring. After adding more salt and pepper to the beef made it taste so much better. If I haven't tried so many other dishes before hand, I would've enjoy this dish a lot more. I would give this another try. Dessert was Strawberry Souffle with strawberry Sauce and strawberry sorbet, and Baked chocolate Souffle with two sauces. Souffles were the things I was looking forward to most. Never tried them before and always thought it would be amazing. Little did I expect to be disappointed. I did not enjoy any of the souffles. The chocolate was too chocolatey to me even though it's one of the popular ones there. The strawberry was better but still didn't enjoy it. They were very fluffy and light. I did not enjoy them, but i'm not indicating they are bad desserts though. Maybe they just weren't meant for me. My bf said the ones he made taste better. I have nothing to compare it to since it was my first time trying them.

    Overall, I will come again to try other dishes. Most definitely affordable dinner. Only down side, must reserve months in advance. =/

    4/3/2013

    2 check-ins

    My dining companion is just as difficult to please as I am when it comes to fine dining. We have been to numerous of overrated restaurants where the food is not as great as what others hype it up to be and we are glad that Gary Danko is not one of them!

    We finally got the chance to try this place out after a 2 month reservation wait and I can say for those who haven't been here before, this place is exceptionally good and worth coming to. The flavors were unusual, in the most wonderful way. What's different about this place is that rather than paying for the price of each entree like most restaurants, you are to select either a 3, 4 or 5 course dinner which is priced at $73, $92 and $107 respectively. You then choose from their vast menu selection the meals you would like categorized under appetizer, fish and seafood, meat, cheeses & dessert. What's great about picking your entrees is that you're not limited to selecting only one meal per category. It's really an endless possibility; you can even have a 5 course dinner with all desserts if you like! The meals were all fantastic and amazing. My top 2 entrees I'd have to recommend to potential diners is their Lemon Pepper Duck and Roast Maine Lobster. Considering I'm not a big fan of duck meat, this place cooked it to perfection for me. It was very tender, juicy and will literally melt in your mouth at first bite. It's absolutely worth coming here to try; you'll taste the difference from every where else. The lobster entree came with a side of creamy potatoe puree and sauteed mushrooms. The lobster was delicious blasting with flavor in every bite. The potatoe puree was a first for me and I must say, I'd prefer this over mashed potatoes! The other dishes we enjoyed were all phernomenal and fulfilling as well.

    While our meals were fantastic and very satisfying, the detail and quality of ingredients used is really what gives this place the full 5 stars. The service here is fantastic - prompt, accomodating and professional. The operation here is well-executed and this place is definitely a legit option for dinner.

    My absolute favorite thing about GD, is the cheese table wheeled out to you, and the explanation of the cheeses.  All we got was this is goat, this is cow and this is... with a cold stare and impatience that was so palpable.  What they were like would of been nice, where they came from, what farm, even the owners name, all of it!  She didn't even bother to explain the cheese at all to us as we pointed to them, she would just start cutting.  I had to remind her to "tell" me what the cheese was like, we both did each time we pointed to one, each time she would start cutting, to hurry it up and get it over with. You could see her inward sigh as we would stop and ask.  Awful, awful, and awful.  

    The timing was so rushed, I could barely eat at the end. The quality of food is far surpassed by so many other good restaurants in SF, this place seems to be a joke and only for the wharf tourists now, who want to pretend they are having an upscale dinner.  So very disappointed in what we did not experience.

    Even the valet didn't know what to do for his job.  He told us to park the car in a space right in front of us instead of taking our keys and car.   We started to move, and saw it was half way up the block.  I said, oh hell no, I wore heels to only to walk 2 feet total in.  I started to get out of the car, and he was clueless, and did not open the door.    I got out instead without waiting for the door, b/c well, I am impatient sometimes (ha!), he then started to hurry back to open my door.   Then he did not guard our spot, and someone did a U turn to grab it fast.  He then tried to get us to move the car further up.  That did not just happen, did it?  It did.  Can I ask what is it a Valet, should do, what is the work job description again?  And upon leaving, the hostess was not even aware that the valet was no longer working, we had to walk back in and take care of business.  

    1. Service is next to none, and if there is any, you wish you could just do it yourself, thanks Laura for not providing a nice Bday dinner.  I should of just told her to go away and googled the name of the cheese and got more information and a smile from google, thank you very much.  
    2. Food, is meh for the prices and totally outdated.
    3. We got more service from the Sommelier than our server.
